    <p class="italic">Note: Answer the two following exercises. This exam is designed to test deep conceptual understanding of induction phenomena.</p>

    <!-- EXERCISE 1: INDUCTION BY VARIABLE MAGNETIC FIELD (10 pts) -->
    <div class="exercise">
        <div class="exercise-head">
            <span>Exercise 1: Coil in a Time-Varying Magnetic Field</span>
            <span>(10 points)</span>
        </div>
        <p>A circular coil of \(N = 500\) turns and radius \(r = 4 \, \text{cm}\) is placed in a region where a uniform magnetic field \(\vec{B}\) exists. The magnetic field is perpendicular to the plane of the coil. The magnitude of \(\vec{B}\) varies with time according to the relation: \(B(t) = 0.05 t + 0.02\) (SI units). The total resistance of the coil circuit is \(R = 4 \, \Omega\).</p>
        
        <div class="figure-box">
            <svg width="400" height="200" viewBox="0 0 400 200">
                <!-- B Field Background Icons (Crosses for Into Page) -->
                <g stroke="#ccc" stroke-width="1">
                    <line x1="50" y1="50" x2="70" y2="70" /> <line x1="70" y1="50" x2="50" y2="70" />
                    <line x1="100" y1="50" x2="120" y2="70" /> <line x1="120" y1="50" x2="100" y2="70" />
                    <line x1="50" y1="120" x2="70" y2="140" /> <line x1="70" y1="120" x2="50" y2="140" />
                    <line x1="100" y1="120" x2="120" y2="140" /> <line x1="120" y1="120" x2="100" y2="140" />
                </g>
                <text x="30" y="40" fill="gray" font-weight="bold">B(t)</text>

                <!-- Circular Coil -->
                <circle cx="200" cy="100" r="60" fill="none" stroke="black" stroke-width="3" />
                
                <!-- Center point and Radius -->
                <circle cx="200" cy="100" r="2" fill="black" />
                <line x1="200" y1="100" x2="252" y2="70" stroke="black" stroke-dasharray="3,3" />
                <text x="225" y="80" font-size="12">r</text>

                <!-- Normal Vector n -->
                <circle cx="200" cy="100" r="8" fill="none" stroke="blue" />
                <line x1="195" y1="95" x2="205" y2="105" stroke="blue" />
                <line x1="205" y1="95" x2="195" y2="105" stroke="blue" />
                <text x="215" y="105" fill="blue" font-weight="bold">n</text>

                <!-- Positive direction of current -->
                <path d="M 270 100 A 70 70 0 0 1 250 150" fill="none" stroke="red" stroke-width="2" marker-end="url(#arrowCur)" />
                <text x="260" y="155" fill="red" font-weight="bold">+</text>

                <defs>
                    <marker id="arrowCur" markerWidth="10" markerHeight="7" refX="0" refY="3.5" orient="auto">
                        <polygon points="0 0, 10 3.5, 0 7" fill="red" />
                    </marker>
                </defs>
            </svg>
            <p class="italic">Figure 1: Coil in a perpendicular variable magnetic field.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="question"><span class="bold">1)</span> Characterize the magnetic flux \(\Phi\) through the coil. 
            Calculate its value at \(t = 0\). (Take \(\vec{n}\) in the same direction as \(\vec{B}\)).</div>

        <div class="question"><span class="bold">2)</span> Using Faraday's Law, determine the expression of the induced electromotive force \(e\). 
            Is the induced current constant or variable? Justify.</div>

        <div class="question"><span class="bold">3)</span> Determine the direction of the induced current \(i\) in the coil. Justify your answer using Lenz's Law.</div>

        <div class="question"><span class="bold">4)</span> Magnitude and Energy aspects:
            <div class="sub-q">a) Calculate the magnitude of the induced current \(i\).</div>
            <div class="sub-q">b) Calculate the total induced charge \(Q\) that passes through a cross-section of the coil wire between \(t_1 = 0\) and \(t_2 = 10 \, \text{s}\).</div>
            <div class="sub-q">c) Determine the electrical power dissipated by the Joule effect in the circuit.</div>
        </div>

        <div class="question"><span class="bold">5)</span> We replace the magnetic field with another field \(B'(t) = 0.2 \cos(100\pi t)\). 
            <div class="sub-q">a) State, without calculation, the nature of the induced current produced in this case.</div>
            <div class="sub-q">b) Give the expression of the new induced e.m.f \(e'(t)\).</div>
        </div>
    </div>

    <!-- EXERCISE 2: ADVANCED RL TRANSIENT ANALYSIS (10 pts) -->
    <div class="exercise">
        <div class="exercise-head">
            <span>Exercise 2: Transient Response and Voltage Differential Equation</span>
            <span>(10 points)</span>
        </div>
        <p>A student builds an RL circuit to study the behavior of a coil of inductance \(L\) and internal resistance \(r\). The circuit includes a DC generator \(E = 12 \, \text{V}\), a resistor \(R = 55 \, \Omega\), and a switch \(K\).</p>

        <div class="figure-box">
            <svg width="500" height="200" viewBox="0 0 500 200">
                <!-- DC Source E (Corrected Connections) -->
                <line x1="60" y1="40" x2="60" y2="85" stroke="black" stroke-width="1.5" />
                <line x1="60" y1="105" x2="60" y2="150" stroke="black" stroke-width="1.5" />
                <!-- Plates -->
                <line x1="45" y1="85" x2="75" y2="85" stroke="black" stroke-width="2" /> <!-- Positive -->
                <line x1="52" y1="105" x2="68" y2="105" stroke="black" stroke-width="5" /> <!-- Negative -->
                <text x="30" y="100" font-weight="bold">E</text>

                <!-- Horizontal Lines -->
                <line x1="60" y1="40" x2="150" y2="40" stroke="black" stroke-width="1.5" />
                <line x1="60" y1="150" x2="420" y2="150" stroke="black" stroke-width="1.5" />

                <!-- Switch K -->
                <circle cx="150" cy="40" r="3" fill="black" />
                <line x1="150" y1="40" x2="190" y2="15" stroke="black" stroke-width="2" />
                <circle cx="200" cy="40" r="3" fill="black" />
                <text x="165" y="10" font-weight="bold">K</text>
                <line x1="200" y1="40" x2="260" y2="40" stroke="black" stroke-width="1.5" />

                <!-- Coil (L, r) -->
                <path d="M 260 40 Q 265 25 270 40 Q 275 25 280 40 Q 285 25 290 40 Q 295 25 300 40 Q 305 25 310 40" fill="none" stroke="blue" stroke-width="2" />
                <text x="265" y="65" fill="blue" font-size="12" font-weight="bold">(L, r)</text>
                <line x1="310" y1="40" x2="420" y2="40" stroke="black" stroke-width="1.5" />

                <!-- Resistor R -->
                <line x1="420" y1="40" x2="420" y2="75" stroke="black" stroke-width="1.5" />
                <rect x="405" y="75" width="30" height="50" fill="none" stroke="black" stroke-width="2" />
                <text x="440" y="105" font-weight="bold">R</text>
                <line x1="420" y1="125" x2="420" y2="150" stroke="black" stroke-width="1.5" />
            </svg>
            <p class="italic">Figure 2: RL circuit schematic.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="question"><span class="bold">1)</span> The switch \(K\) is closed at \(t = 0\).
            <div class="sub-q">a) Which component is responsible for the delay in the establishment of the current? Justify by mentioning the self-induced e.m.f.</div>
            <div class="sub-q">b) Using the law of addition of voltages, show that the differential equation for the voltage \(u_R(t)\) is: 
                $$\frac{du_R}{dt} + \frac{R+r}{L}u_R = \frac{RE}{L}$$
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="question"><span class="bold">2)</span> The solution to this equation is \(u_R(t) = U_{max}(1 - e^{-t/\tau})\).
            <div class="sub-q">a) Express \(U_{max}\) and \(\tau\) in terms of the circuit constants.</div>
            <div class="sub-q">b) At steady state, \(u_R = 11 \, \text{V}\). Calculate the internal resistance \(r\) of the coil.</div>
            <div class="sub-q">c) Calculate the initial rate of change \(\left( \frac{du_R}{dt} \right)_{t=0}\) of the voltage across the resistor.</div>
        </div>

        <div class="question"><span class="bold">3)</span> Energy transitions:
            <div class="sub-q">a) The magnetic energy stored at steady state is \(10 \, \text{mJ}\). Calculate the current \(I_0\) and the inductance \(L\).</div>
            <div class="sub-q">b) Calculate the magnetic energy stored in the coil at the instant \(t = \tau\).</div>
            <div class="sub-q">c) Compare the power provided by the generator to the power dissipated by the Joule effect in the whole circuit at steady state. Conclude.</div>
        </div>

        <div class="question"><span class="bold">4)</span> Sketch the shape of \(u_L(t)\). Specify its value at \(t=0\) and for \(t \to \infty\).</div>
    </div>

    <!-- MARKING SCHEME -->
    <div class="marking-scheme">
        <div class="header">
            <h1>MARKING SCHEME (BARÈME)</h1>
        </div>
        
        <h3 class="bold">Exercise 1 (10 pts)</h3>
        <table class="scheme-table">
            <tr><th>Q</th><th>Expected Answer / Distribution of Points</th><th class="pts">Points</th></tr>
            <tr><td>1</td><td>\(\Phi = N B S \cos(0)\). At \(t=0, B=0.02\). \(\Phi_0 = 500 \cdot 0.02 \cdot \pi \cdot (0.04)^2 \approx 0.0503 \, \text{Wb}\).</td><td class="pts">1.0</td></tr>
            <tr><td>2</td><td>\(e = -d\Phi/dt = -N S (dB/dt) = -500 \cdot \pi \cdot 0.04^2 \cdot 0.05 \approx -0.126 \, \text{V}\). Constant since derivative is constant.</td><td class="pts">1.5</td></tr>
            <tr><td>3</td><td>\(\Phi\) increases \(\implies B_{induced}\) opposes \(\vec{B}\). By RHR, current is counter-clockwise (opp. to + direction).</td><td class="pts">1.5</td></tr>
            <tr><td>4.a</td><td>\(I = |e|/R = 0.126 / 4 = 0.0315 \, \text{A}\).</td><td class="pts">1.0</td></tr>
            <tr><td>4.b</td><td>\(Q = I \cdot \Delta t = 0.0315 \cdot 10 = 0.315 \, \text{C}\).</td><td class="pts">1.0</td></tr>
            <tr><td>4.c</td><td>\(P = R I^2 = 4 \cdot (0.0315)^2 \approx 3.97 \times 10^{-3} \, \text{W}\).</td><td class="pts">1.0</td></tr>
            <tr><td>5.a</td><td>Alternating induced current (AC).</td><td class="pts">1.0</td></tr>
            <tr><td>5.b</td><td>\(e' = -NS(dB'/dt) = -500 \cdot \pi \cdot 0.04^2 \cdot [-0.2 \cdot 100\pi \sin(100\pi t)] \approx 50.3 \sin(100\pi t) \, \text{V}\).</td><td class="pts">2.0</td></tr>
        </table>

        <h3 class="bold" style="margin-top:20px;">Exercise 2 (10 pts)</h3>
        <table class="scheme-table">
            <tr><th>Q</th><th>Expected Answer / Distribution of Points</th><th class="pts">Points</th></tr>
            <tr><td>1.a</td><td>The coil. Self-induced e.m.f \(e = -L di/dt\) opposes current growth (Lenz's Law).</td><td class="pts">1.0</td></tr>
            <tr><td>1.b</td><td>Derivation of diff. eq. starting from \(E = u_L + u_R\). Substitution of \(i = u_R/R\).</td><td class="pts">2.0</td></tr>
            <tr><td>2.a</td><td>\(U_{max} = RE/(R+r)\); \(\tau = L/(R+r)\).</td><td class="pts">1.0</td></tr>
            <tr><td>2.b</td><td>\(11 = 55 \cdot 12 / (55 + r) \implies r = 5 \, \Omega\).</td><td class="pts">1.0</td></tr>
            <tr><td>2.c</td><td>\((du_R/dt)_{t=0} = U_{max}/\tau = RE/L\). Value calc: \(55 \cdot 12 / 0.5 = 1320 \, \text{V/s}\).</td><td class="pts">1.0</td></tr>
            <tr><td>3.a</td><td>\(I_0 = 11/55 = 0.2 \, \text{A}\). \(L = 2W / I_0^2 = 0.02 / 0.04 = 0.5 \, \text{H}\).</td><td class="pts">1.5</td></tr>
            <tr><td>3.b</td><td>At \(t=\tau, i = 0.63 I_0\). \(W_{\tau} = 0.5 L (0.63 I_0)^2 = 0.63^2 \cdot W_{steady} \approx 3.97 \, \text{mJ}\).</td><td class="pts">1.0</td></tr>
            <tr><td>3.c</td><td>At steady state, \(P_{gen} = E I_0 = 2.4 \, \text{W}\). \(P_{joule} = (R+r) I_0^2 = 60 \cdot 0.04 = 2.4 \, \text{W}\). All power is dissipated as heat.</td><td class="pts">1.0</td></tr>
            <tr><td>4</td><td>\(u_L(0) = E = 12 \, \text{V}\). \(u_L(\infty) = r I_0 = 5 \cdot 0.2 = 1 \, \text{V}\). Graph shows exponential decay.</td><td class="pts">0.5</td></tr>
        </table>
    </div>
</div>

